  <h2>Why Selling a Fire Damaged Home the Traditional Way Is So Hard</h2>
  <p>Listing a fire damaged property with a real estate agent isn't impossible, but it's slow. Conventional buyers can't get financing on a property with structural or smoke damage — lenders won't approve it. That narrows your buyer pool to cash investors anyway, but you'd go through months of showings, lowball offers, and negotiations to get there.</p>
  <p>There's also the insurance question. Some sellers want to wait for the insurance payout before deciding what to do. That's your call. But if you've already decided you don't want to rebuild — or the insurance settlement isn't going to cover what you thought — a direct cash sale gives you certainty right now instead of more waiting.</p>

  <h2>What Determines the Cash Offer on a Fire Damaged Home</h2>
  <p>I'm going to be straight with you: a fire damaged home sells for less than a fully repaired one. That's just the math. What I factor in is the after-repair value of the property, the realistic cost to restore it, and what I need to make the project work. I don't lowball and hope you don't know better — I walk you through the numbers so the offer makes sense.</p>
  <p>What affects the offer:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Extent of structural damage vs. cosmetic smoke and soot</li>
    <li>Whether the roof, electrical, or HVAC were affected</li>
    <li>Location and underlying property value in Wichita</li>
    <li>What the surrounding comparable sales look like</li>
  </ul>
  <p>If you've already gotten an insurance payout or estimate, share it — it helps me give you a more accurate offer faster.</p>

